WORLD CUP PENALTY SHOOTOUTS ANALYSIS AND WINNER PREDICTION¶

In this notebook, I will attempt to go for an exploratory data analysis of the penalty shootouts from worlcup since it has started up to the 2022 edition.

First will take a look at the data (which is a classic),

then we'll try to visualize the data to:

Goal post zones¶

  • See which goal post zone has the highest chances of penalty conversion
  • See whether these differences are statistically significant to make any kind of inference
  • Look at both conversion rates and zone preferences in terms of zone per penalty number

Country Performances¶

  • Take a deeper dive to compare country performances in terms of conversion rates and wins

Dexterity trends¶

  • Compare conversion rates from a dexterity stand point
  • Map out conversion rates and number of shots per foot (left vs right) per goalpost zone

Goal keeper trends¶

  • Take a look at goal keeper preferences dive-wise
  • see which country has the most saves across all competitions

Elimination predictions using K-Nearest neighbors¶

Winner Prediction with KNN based on Country key features¶

Hypothesis testing with Chi2 Squared¶

In [30]:
# Importing libraries for Chi2 Test
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

as seen from preevious visualizations the 3rd position has an impressive record of 88% success rate with 0% shots parried by goallkeepers, here we'll putting this observation to the test using Chi2 Squared! the null hypothesis would be that there is indeeed a relationship between the location (zone) and connversion rate,so this is what we'll be trying to inspect in this analysis. consequently, the alternative hypothesis would be that theree isn't a relationship! we'll take a 5% confidence level iif p-value is below 5% then we'll accept that the 88% conversion rate is less than 5% likely to be thanks to luck.

In [31]:
# Adding missed shots to build Contingency Tables

scored['missed'] = (scored['Zone Count'] - scored['Goals']).astype('int64')
scored

In [1326]:
# Building our contingency Table
contingency_table = scored[['Goals', 'missed']].values
In [1327]:
chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
In [1812]:
# Setting the significance level at 5%
significance_level = 0.05
In [1814]:
# Calculating degrees of freedom (R - 1) x (C - 1)
degrees_of_freedom = (contingency_table.shape[0] - 1)*(contingency_table.shape[1] - 1)
print(f"we have {degrees_of_freedom} for this test")

we have 8 for this test
In [1330]:
print(f"Chi-squared statistic: {chi2:.3}")
print(f"p-value: {p_value:.3%}")

Chi-squared statistic: 7.55
p-value: 47.847%
In [1331]:
# decision
if significance_level > p_value:
    print("Reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis")

Fail to reject the null hypothesis

This result means that there's 47% that the 88% is just due to random events or other reasons tthat fall out of reach of this dataset

def get_participation(w_teams, win):
    participations = []
    counter = 0
    for i, team in enumerate(w_teams):
        counter = 0
        for j, team2 in enumerate(win):
            if team2 == team:
                counter += 1
        participations.append(counter)
        
    return participations

LET'S EXPERIMENT WITH AN AGGREGATED DATAFRAME¶

Here in this test case we'll aggregate the dataframe by Game and Country and try and squeeze out some more meaningful features in an attempt to make a prediction model based solely on the teams past performances.

the biggest drawback in this approach is that 1- the dataset we'll be confined in a much smaller size, given that we have only about 34 countries in total, but the features we'll be able to extract will carry much more information as far as building a model that would make a prediction of the potential winner in a given clash.

I think such model will offer much more value rather than trying to predict the "eliminatory penalty" especially if the Data itself is not conducive to such analysis.

Long story short, what do I know? let's just mess around and see where my intuition takes us!
